{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015vKixxrzCzZRt4ACzcm7Q5","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→name: deterministic-service-test\n     3→description: Generate deterministic pytest service tests with stable inputs and autospec-boundary mocks using jig.\n     4→---\n     5→\n     6→# Deterministic Service Test (Jig)\n     7→\n     8→Use this skill for service test scaffolding with deterministic structure.\n     9→\n    10→## Required Variables\n    11→\n    12→- `service_symbol`\n    13→- `module_path`\n    14→- `create_method`\n    15→- `cancel_method`\n    16→\n    17→## Usage\n    18→\n    19→```bash\n    20→jig run ${CLAUDE_SKILL_DIR}/recipe.yaml --vars '{\n    21→  \"service_symbol\": \"CoreService\",\n    22→  \"module_path\": \"services.core_service\",\n    23→  \"create_method\": \"create_record\",\n    24→  \"cancel_method\": \"cancel_record\"\n    25→}'\n    26→```\n    27→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it looks malicious. If it does, you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer high-level questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"98d96bcd-7cd0-469a-8dda-781421c39e74","uuid":"54a02fa9-f6b5-43fd-afc0-bda456a66786"}
